{{Infobox comics nationality <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics--> |image = <!-- filename format only --> |imagesize = <!-- default 250 --> |caption = |alt = |date = 19th century |pub# = <!-- upto 5 --> |title# = <!-- upto 5 --> |person# = <!-- upto 5 --> |series# = <!-- upto 5 --> |character# = <!-- upto 5 --> |lang# = <!-- upto 4 --> |related# = <!-- upto 3 --> }} '''European comics''' are comics produced in [[Europe]]. The ''[[comic album]]'' is a very common printed medium. The typical ''album'' is printed in large format, generally with high quality paper and colouring, roughly [[ISO 216|A4]]-sized, approx. 21x30 centimetres (8.4x11.6 in), has around 40–60 pages, but examples with more than 100 pages are common. While sometimes referred to as [[graphic novel]]s, this term is rarely used in Europe, and is not always applicable as albums often consist of separate short stories, placing them somewhere halfway between a comic book and a graphic novel. The European comic genres vary from the humorous adventure vein, such as ''[[The Adventures of Tintin]]'' and ''[[Asterix]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://europeisnotdead.com/video/images-of-europe/european-comics/|title=European Comics|date=2013-04-29|access-date=2017-06-30|language=en-US}}</ref> to more adult subjects like ''[[Tex Willer]]'', ''[[Diabolik]]'', and ''[[Thorgal]]''.
==History== The roots of European on-paper comics date back to 18th century [[caricature]]s (mocking others styles or behaviors) and illustrated picture books such as [[Wilhelm Busch]]'s [[Max and Moritz]]. The early 19th century [[Switzerland|Swiss]] artist [[Rodolphe Töpffer]] is regarded by many as the "father of the modern comic" and his publication ''[[Histoire de M. Vieux Bois]]'' is sometimes called the first "comic book".<ref>[[Scott McCloud|McCloud, Scott]], ''[[Understanding Comics|Understanding Comics: The Invisible Art]]''. New York: Harper Collins & Kitchen Sink Press. 1994. {{ISBN|0-06-097625-X}}, pg 17.</ref> [[Franco-Belgian comics]], [[Spanish comics]], and [[Italian comics]] are historically amongst the dominant scenes of European comics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2016/11/moebius-and-beyond-an-introduction-to-european-com.html|title=Moebius and Beyond: An Introduction to European Comics|work=pastemagazine.com|access-date=2017-06-30|language=en}}</ref>
Earlier, paintings, depicting stories in subsequent frames, using descriptive text resembling bubbles-text, were used in murals, one such example witten in [[Greek_language|Greek]], dating to the [[2nd century]], found in [[Capitolias#Archaeology|Capitolias]], today in [[Jordan]]<ref>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/ancient-comics-line-roman-era-tomb-jordan-180970400/</ref>.
==Festivals== A number of festivals celebrating comic art are held around Europe. These include:
* [[Amadora BD]], [[Portugal]] * [[Angoulême International Comics Festival]], [[France]] * [[Fumetto International Comics Festival]], [[Lucerne]], [[Switzerland]] * [[Helsinki Comics Festival]], [[Finland]] * [[International Comics Festival "Salon stripa"]], [[Serbia]] * [[International Festival of Comics and Games]], [[Poland]] * [[The Lakes International Comic Art Festival]], [[Kendal]], [[United Kingdom]] * [[Lille Comics Festival]], [[France]] * [[Lucca Comics & Games]], [[Italy]]
==See also== ;National traditions * [[Franco-Belgian comics]] * [[Belgian comics]] * [[British comics]] * [[Czech comics]] * [[Dutch Comics]] * [[German comics]] * [[Hungarian comics]] * [[Italian comics]] * [[Polish comics]] * [[Portuguese comics]] * [[Serbian comics]] * [[Spanish comics]]
