{{Refimprove|date=October 2008}} {{Infobox Theatre |name = Thalia Theater |image = Hh-thalia.jpg |image_size = 250px |caption = Thalia Theater front view. |address = Raboisen 67 |city = [[Hamburg]], Germany |country = |designation = |latitude = |longitude = |architect = |owner = [[Hamburg|Free and Hanseatic City of Hamburg]] |capacity = |type = |opened = 1843 |yearsactive = |rebuilt = |closed = |othernames = |production = |currentuse = |website = http://www.thalia-theater.de/ }}
The '''Thalia Theater''' is one of the three state-owned theatres in [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]]. It was founded in 1843 by [[Charles Maurice Schwartzenberger]] and named after the [[muse]] [[Thalia (muse)|Thalia]]. Today, it is home to one of Germany's most famous ensembles and stages around 9 new plays per season. Current theatre manager is [[Joachim Lux]], who in 2009/10 succeeded [[Ulrich Khuon]].
In addition to its main building, located in the street ''Raboisen'' in the [[Altstadt, Hamburg|Altstadt]] quarter near the [[Binnenalster]] and [[Gerhart-Hauptmann-Platz]] in Hamburg's inner city, the theatre operates a smaller stage, used for experimental plays, the '''Thalia in der Gaußstraße''', located in the borough of [[Altona, Hamburg|Altona]].
==Plays== In October 1991 [[Ruth Berghaus]] directed [[Bertolt Brecht]]'s ''[[In The Jungle of Cities]]'' (German: ''Im Dickicht der Städte'') as part of a series of 'related texts', as she called them (which also included [[Georg Büchner|Büchner]]'s ''[[Danton's Death]]'').<ref name="meech54">Meech (1994, 54).</ref>
